SIMPLE: pupil
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pupil
<hw>Pu"pil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>pupille</ets>,
n. fem., L. <ets>pupilla</ets> the pupil of the eye, originally dim. of
<ets>pupa</ets> a girl. See <er>Puppet</er>, and cf. <er>Pupil</er> a
scholar.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The aperture in the iris; the
sight, apple, or black of the eye. See the Note under <er>Eye</er>, and
<er>Iris</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pin-hole pupil</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>the pupil
of the eye when so contracted (as it sometimes is in typhus, or opium
poisoning) as to resemble a pin hole.</cd>
<rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pupil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pupil
<hw>Pu"pil</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>pupille</ets>, n. masc. &
fem., L. <ets>pupillus</ets>, <ets>pupilla</ets>, dim. of
<ets>pupus</ets> boy, <ets>pupa</ets> girl. See <er>Puppet</er>, and cf.
<er>Pupil</er> of the eye.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A youth or scholar of
either sex under the care of an instructor or tutor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Too far in years to be a <qex>pupil</qex> now.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tutors should behave reverently before their
<qex>pupils</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person under a guardian; a ward.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Civil Law)</fld> <def>A boy or a girl under the age
of puberty, that is, under fourteen if a male, and under twelve if a
female.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Learner; disciple; tyro. -- See
<er>Scholar</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pupilage</ent>⟦br⟧
